The ‘bee car’ that avoids collisions
To advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by the nature, especially of bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, by imitating the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers from Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Center have made this small robot in collaboration with the Advanced Science and Technology Research Center of the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C represents the rise of the Nissan safety shield.
This robot will allow brand vehicles to prevent collisions.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space in an oval shape that resembles the Nissan safety shield.
But most importantly, the bee's eyes are composed, able to see at an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, allowing it to fly without interruption inside its own personal space.
In order to recreate this visual function, engineers developed what is called a laser range finder.
This detects obstacles that are at a distance of two meters and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to this object and sends a signal to the microprocessor immediately to avoid the obstacle.
“At the moment he detects an obstacle, the little robot will imitate the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by bifurcating its wheels by 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other existing system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
If that were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Movement Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be turned upwards or downwards, or diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and depending on what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions like bees.
For this reason, Nissan used a rotational function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid obstacles.
Every second this device must only process information and act according to that data.
It doesn’t need to keep the information or the intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, so it can work continuously with just a few dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise you, but we’re not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes.”
This is the first because of the development of new instantaneous collision prevention technologies, a technology that will be introduced in serial cars in a decade, according to Nissan.
The robot runs with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device to a satellite navigation GPS system to guide the driver to its destination by avoiding road obstacles.
