Rafael Correa in Quito this Monday.
Refounding the Republic around 21st Century Socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his counterparts and friends, it was the third to put a new draft constitution to the vote.
Mission accomplished as 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to official results accounting for 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" got 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were white votes.
In order for the draft constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit of the polling stations and a countdown from a non-governmental organization announced a wide victory of the "yes" between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa claimed the victory of his draft constitution on the night of Sunday to Monday.
“The Constitution has triumphed in an overwhelming way,” he had assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians at Guayaquil Governorate headquarters, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales as well as his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which took place quietly according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), covered a 444-point text consolidating the “new socialism” defended by the president.
The draft Constitution consecrates the power of the State on the economy, reserving it with the "development planning" of a country living mainly from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and the currencies sent by its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants enhanced powers to the Head of State, which will be able to carry out up to two consecutive four-year terms and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and will hold a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further strengthens the principle of free health and education services that the President has begun to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It finally provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for U.S. anti-drug operations.
19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts, who had been held captive for ten days in the desert, were brought back this Monday afternoon healthy and safe to the Egyptian capital.
In the morning, they had been released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in shape, the hostages arrived at about 3:30 p.m. on board a special plane at al-Maza military base, which was taken up at Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, on board helicopters to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, to undergo examinations there.
They are "healthy" and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers," Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the spot.
Captured on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this hostage group had been voted out of hiding by 35 unknown hijackers.
It includes 11 tourists – five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian – as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, one border guard and the director of the Egyptian agency, the organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, taken on board two helicopters, had launched the assault in the night just before dawn.
“There was an exchange of shots, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fleeing,” said the official who demanded anonymity.
He said 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "clair" unit had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
Italian diplomat Franco Frattini mentioned Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men of the secret services, special forces," he said, without further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
On the eve, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol a 4x4 vehicle on board of which the kidnappers were, killing six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army had claimed that they were linked to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan-United Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
