A dwarf in the chick
In America, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programs that link the use of prescription information, in any case, to the agreement of the person concerned.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it's all about entrusting its chicken to a dwarf," Richard Dicket, the program's creator used to manage prescription drugs, told the Washington Post.
Insurance companies depend on the insurance premium and the insured capital in case of damage, on the health status of the client who is present, and if they consider the risk to be too high, they do not even insur it.
In the past, they sent the candidates to a medical examination, and they signed an insurance contract with them only after learning of the results.
For ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, it is easily provided to pharmacies, data on the person's purchases of medicines in the last eighteen months. From that, the program determines that the person's health is itself, and that the person's health is ill.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts it in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk coefficient, so there is no longer much to do to the insurer other than paperwork. However, small problems may still appear.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraines or heat bumps, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others do not.
Companies have evolved in research and data analysis, and they need to ask the patient for permission before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced by the authorities, even if they have not been sanctioned for their failures in the past.
Recently, some companies have also processed the results of laboratory tests, and linked them to data on drug consumption, thus enabling them to provide an even more accurate portrait of the patient's health status.
More and more companies have access to data, and controlling usage is becoming increasingly difficult in parallel.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill on the extension of the authority control circle for data-suppliing companies is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the person concerned.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his or her consent, since if he or she refuses, insurance does not sign an insurance contract with him or her.
Thus, and ultimately, chickens depend on the kindness of the rabbit.
