The wreckage of Steve Fosset's plane, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada Desert, was found.
The debris was found on a 3,000-metre-altitude plateau in the Mammonth Lakes Sierra Nevada area on the California-Nevada border.
Inside the plane, however, no human remains.
The sheriff of Madera County, John Anderson, eased the doubts that remained: “The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have the confirmation that this is the one Steve Fosset was travelling on the day he disappeared,” he said at a press conference.
The sheriff said no human remains were found on the plane or in the vicinity.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was deemed dead.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Bureau (NTSB) said that a few hours after the debris was detected, a team of investigators sent to the site identified the device: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fossett de Nedala took a flight from Neva.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some personal effects of Fosset were found by a couple around their Mammoth Lakes home.
These are two documents bearing the name of Fosset, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a pull.
Fossett's search was interrupted a month after his disappearance.
